jokbon: 
-tutorial
YAGPDB.xyz: 
Welcome to Factions
This is an exciting game for team battles
Alone, it will be quite difficult, because more players in your faction, more territory can be protected protected!
Let's start with the /f help command, here you will see list of the main commands.
Now it's time to create your faction! Do /f create *Name of your faction*.
You are given 20 power at the start. Hoping, you didn't die somewhere along the way. Write /f power to see how much power you have. After all, it will be needed to claim chunks for your faction.
Oh yes, to protect your stuff you need claims, for this write /f claim. You will claim one chunk of 16x16 blocks. The number of power all players in your faction have, is summed up, one claim costs 2 power. Be careful if you lose power, then your enemies will be able to owerclaim your territory! Those who against you! The goal of this game is to find Allies and attack enemies together! Stock up on tnt! Thats how to get into the territory of your enemies, but be quick, because if they are afraid of you and leave the game like miserable rats, you will have 15 minutes to bomb their chests and steal stuff, or else their lands will become invulnerable!

Don't worry, I'm not using these old things, because the old stuff will throw a problem in any version, because they have been set to decapitated. 

So if I'm using something they will remove, my IDE will tell me about it.
A good example would be`(Strike through is telling me that it will get removed):

From: `ClaimManager.class.newInstance()`
To: `ClaimManager.class.getConstructor().newInstance()`

That does the same, just with the new approach it will be save to use in java 18.

tobero: 
I'm sorry, but I couldn't allow a 0.02 ms loss (average of many runs) per fi statement. I now reduced if statements drastically and replaced them with boot up setups. This just loads differnet faction implementations (Like a local file system one or a mysql one, as mysql needs to ync whihc would require many if statements when Id done it with the old code)
tobero: 
As I said, this plugin has performance first, user friendliness second.. and last but not least the RAM usage - You could probably guess
leonzockt01: 
Has performance ever been an actual problem? On my side, it always worked really, really well (as long as nobody tried to claim a thousand chunks at once)
tobero: 
Yeah, it was a problem with beta because (it still does that) the RAM & CPU usage scaled with the player count too much for just a faction plugin. That's why I fixed it, now the usage is nearly nothing anymore
tobero: 
It only was a problem with 1000 factions or so because everything kept loaded
tobero: 
But now 1000 factions don't make a difference anymore
tobero: 
And jakbon told me the plugin is 3 times performant than SaberFactions

tobero: 
because mongoDb sends data not at once, it sends it over a pipleline, meaning the plugin can process data while data is still being read. Meaning the players are getting loaded faster, unlike mysql where you have to wait for the full response
tobero: 
Since my coding style changed so quickly (Good direction) I ended up down a rabbit hole of changing the entire codebase. Now due to massive changes I have decided to clean the whole project as it turns out the code really sucks to put it lightly. Since I was also planning on porting to Fabric, Forge, and Quillt, it was time to improve the improved (Ha do you get it? Improve the improved) factions code again anyway. The code structure will now be divided into different branches, where the core will contain all APIs. These APIs are then customized for each game version. This will take some time, but will make it easier to maintain the plugin. On top of that there will be fewer bugs as I will release as many test versions as possible so that they can be thoroughly tested.
tobero: 
Btw thanks goes to Callum, who validated my point, on how much he code base sucks.
tobero: 
Thanks for your help

tobero:

Essentials has stuff to be used with placeholder API if that what you mean but essentials can't parse them for use in chat. Don't think edits the tab list or other areas.
strafey.msqd: 
Wait, so what is it specifically that is t working between the two?

I don‚Äôt specifically know what Placebolder API does, it‚Äôs only on my server because Tablist requires it
josh65: 
Placeholder API allows getting information from plugins using variables like `%server_time%` would get and display the world time on chat, scoreboard, tablist or others. Essentials doesn't support getting that information so when people want to get the faction name a players and have it show in chat before there message it doesnt work.

strafey.msqd: 
```java
label: "wild" # The command will look like this: /dirt
description: "Receive 64 dirt" # The description you can see when using help
usage: "/wild" # The usage that is getting displayed to the user
aliases: # The aliases the command is known as

permission: "aliases.wild" # The permission a player requires to use the command
no-permission-message: "You can't use this command, due to lack of permission" # The message that's getting displayed when the player doesn't have the permission

# -------( Actions )-------
# [actionbar] <message> - Send an actionbar to the player
# [broadcast] <message> - Send a message to all players
# [console] <command> - Execute a command in console
# [player] <command> - Execute a command as player
# [message] <message> - Send a message to a player
# [sound] <sound> <volume> <pitch> - Play a sound. Sounds can be found. List of sounds: https://hub.spigotmc.org/javadocs/bukkit/org/bukkit/Sound.html
# [title] <title> [subtitle] [fade in] [stay] [fade out] Send a title to a player. Underscores will be replaced with spaces.
#
# -------( Placeholders )-------
# {player} - the player execution the command

execution:
  - "{player} rtp world Wild"```
strafey.msqd: 
This is what I've got here
tobero: 
Replace the {} with []
tobero: 
That will fix your issue

tobero: 
So, I created a quick example for the manage faction gui. Currently all icons are chosen at random and don't make any sense to the thing they actually relate too.

I want to pack as many things as possible into guis, because it's way better for players on mobile, xbox, etc when they don't have to type everything into the text line
Attachments:
[unknown.png]
https://cdn.discordapp.com/attachments/819947051059118111/1020393424949624872/unknown.png?ex=664843ae&is=6646f22e&hm=9e6e851dca81313cf7fac6eba60ad911177b40efd7602a68672f4b62a0e53b0a&

josh65: 
Looks fine really. Most server ive seen also have a layout like that
tobero: 
Okay, then I'll go with something like that as long as I don't see something better
tobero: 
Btw, do you think it would make sense for me to allow custom gui creating using python? I'm just asking, because it's quite simple and I don't have to create a custom logic processor for the actions, etc.
But on the other hand, the server you're running this plugin on would require python and when you try to customize things you need to know python
josh65: 
How would that work user side. Would it be script file edit or in game?
tobero: 
There would be a directory within the plugin folder, where you can edit the python scripts
josh65: 
With instructions on what to change and some examples in the file it shouldn't matter if the user doesnt know anything on python and installing it isnt too hard. If it quiker to do could try and see if users have a difficulty with it
tobero: 
This would go from that: ```yml
title: "Manage {faction}"
items:
  faction-icon:
    slot: 4
    on-click: "gui/faction-icon.action"
    item: "{faction#getIcon}"
```

To: 

```python
import ImprovedFactions

def manage_faction_gui(gui: Gui, user: Player):
  gui.set_title("Manage " + user.get_faction().get_display())
  gui.setContent(4, user.get_faction().get_icon(), edit_icon) 

def edit_icon(gui: Gui, user: Player):
  user.open_gui("faction_icon_editor", user.get_faction())


ImprovedFactions.customize_gui("manage_faction", manage_faction_gui)
```

Something like that

With this, I would just run this thing once on startup and fire some events on it's side.
tobero: 
The problem with the yml thing is, I would have to manage routing etc myself, while in the lower one, I just receive the event that the user wants to set the title
josh65: 
I say try python one first and if it goes well it can be left as is, mabye in the future some text based UI can be added to the script so editing is easier for more users. If it doesnt then change to the .yml implementation.
tobero: 
Okay, I'll see if it makes sense to us python. There are some things that annoy me a little bit about it.
The user would be required to have python installed. And the other thing is, that python is pretty slow, which would force me into using multi threading. That would lead to many issues too.

Will probably just write my own logic processor for that
tobero: 
Okay, will do it the easiest way. I'll just save the gui files unreadable for the user, so they can only edit the guis using the ingame gui editor

  regeneration-time: 60 # 60 Minutes

tobero: 
Looks like a corrupted file. Redownload it and try it again
dupdk: 
is when you set /f admin reset
tobero: 
No. Happens when the internet does what the internet does: It lost a package when sending the file to you, the checksum still provided the correct result and your browser thought the file has finished downloading.

Long story short: It's common for files to get corrupted while downloading, so just redownload it and it should work the next time

tobero: 
```yml
label: "spawn"
description: "Teleports you to the spawn"
usage: "/spawn"
aliases:
  - "lobby"
  - "hub"
permission: "command.spawn"
no-permission-message: "You can't use this command, due to lack of permission"
error-message: "Something went wrong while executing your command"
execution:
 - "[player] teleport {player} 0 0 0"
 - "[title] &eYou_teleported_to_spawn"
```

This would be a spawn command example using simple command aliases

tobero: 
Here's the section for the zones:
```yml
zones:
  safezone:
    translation-id: "safezone"
    registry: "__glb:safezone__"
    color: 0x00bfff
    managed: true # Determines if the claim will be handled by improved factions
    protection: true
    pvp: false
  warzone:
    translation-id: "warzone"
    registry: "__glb:warzone__"
    color: 0xb30000
    managed: true # Determines if the claim will be handled by improved factions
    protection: true
    pvp: true
  unclaimable:
    translation-id: "unclaimable"
    registry: "__glb:unclaimable__"
    color: 0xb30000
    managed: false # This will just prevent the chunks from being claimed
```

Full file is attached
Attachments:
[config.yml]
prefix: "¬ß8[¬ßeIF¬ß8]¬ß7" # This text is in-front of all messages a player will receive from improved factions
faction:
  max-registry-length: 10 # The amount of characters allowed for a faction registry. Registries are the id of your faction. Default: 10 characters
  max-display-length: 10 # The amount of characters the name, that'll be visible to players can be. Defaults to 10 characters
  max-tag-length: 3 # Specify how long a faction tag can get. Tags should be short identifiers for a faction. Default: 3 characters
  registry-regex: '[^a-zA-Z0-9-_]' # !DANGER! This is a regex. This regex is used to determine which characters should get replaced with spaces. The default value will replace everything that isn't a letter, number, underscore or dash. When you change this to a regex that allows illegal characters, your file system doesn't support, it will cause the plugin to crash. Leave it defaulted unless you know what you're doing
  active-member-threshold: 60 # This threshold is measured in days. When a player hasn't been online for X days, he'll no longer count to the faction's power. Defaults to 60 days
  default: # Every newly created factions will start-out with these values. Already created ones won't be affected
    motd: "Newly created faction" # The message of the day for this faction
    tag: "IFF" # Tags are short identifiers for factions. Will mostly be used in chats or tab lists.
    open-type: "INVITE_ONLY" # Defines whether players can join this faction. Options: PUBLIC; INVITE_ONLY; CLOSED. PUBLIC -> Everyone can join. Faction will get listed in the search menu. INVITE_ONLY -> Faction will get listed, but everyone wanting to join has to receive a invite from a person permitted to do so. CLOSED -> Nobody can join, faction doesn't get listed
    frozen: false # !DANGER! A frozen factions can't interact with anything anymore until unfrozen again. This feature exists, so your moderators can take a look at factions without the faction's state being able to get changed. Can only be set / unset using admin commands
    permanent: false # !WARNING! Marks a faction to exist even when no players are in it anymore. This allows faction owners to leave. Should only be changed when you know what you're doing.
    start-balance: 0 # The amount of money a faction has when starting out. Note: This might cause money glitches, when creating a factions is free (or at least below the start balance) (Creating factions, transfer the money to owner account, delete, repeat). Might get fixed in future versions
    start-power: 20 # The power each faction starts out with
    start-max-power: 100 # The max power a faction can gain

language:
  default-local: "en_us" # Change this to your server main language, as long as a file with this name exists within lang/ folder

world:
  disabled-worlds: # A list of worlds that don't allow improved factions
  #  - "Disabled faction world"
  enabled-worlds: # When having too many worlds and only want a small amount to be faction worlds, use this list. This list will calculate a disabled worlds list
#  - "Enabled faction world"

number-symbols: # These symbols will be used to shorten a number for better display in text or gui
  k: 1000
  m: 1000000
  b: 1000000000
  t: 1000000000000
  q: 1000000000000000
  Q: 1000000000000000000

zones:
  safezone:
    translation-id: "safezone"
    registry: "__glb:safezone__"
    color: 0x00bfff
    managed: true # Determines if the claim will be handled by improved factions
    protection: true
    pvp: false
  warzone:
    translation-id: "warzone"
    registry: "__glb:warzone__"
    color: 0xb30000
    managed: true # Determines if the claim will be handled by improved factions
    protection: true
    pvp: true
  unclaimable:
    translation-id: "unclaimable"
    registry: "__glb:unclaimable__"
    color: 0xb30000
    managed: false # This will just prevent the chunks from being claimed

################# Advanced config options #####################
#
# A database always syncs up ith the server, meaning that you can run this plugin on multiple
# server while still keeping your data synchronized
#
# Useful with Multipaper, Velocity, BungeeCord, etc
#
# This will save RAM on the minecraft server side.
# Only one database should be selected with true
# When no database is selected, it will run locally using the plugin data folder
#
storage:
  use-mysql: false
  mysql: # Only when use-mysql is set to true
    host: "localhost" # Host is the ip address of the mysql server
    port: "3306" # Port is the port the service is listing at
    user: "root" # The user this plugin is allowed to use. Note: Don't use root, create a new user with permissions to just manage improved factions tables
    password: "1234" # The password of the user given above

################# Performance #####################
# These settings can seriously screw your server when not being set perfectly.
# Bad settings might cause too much of ram being used or your cpu cycles being wasted.
# Be careful when editing it. Keep a backup and benchmark before putting it into production.

performance:
  ram:
    claim-garbage-collector: 6000 # Define how fast claims get unloaded again. Default: 6000 ticks (5 minutes). 20 ticks = 1 second. Smaller value will reduce RAM usage, but increases stress on the cpu for cleaning. A too small value will overload your disk, because everything needed to be loaded and instantly being rejected from ram again

What tha heck is faction flying
saschava: 
And how dissable it
tobero: 
It's a extension. It's not installed until you install it.
Factin flying is a command allowing your players to use /f fly in their claimed chunks. Some faction servers have it
saschava: 
Is there command to dissable it for all
tobero: 
You mean /f fly?
tobero: 
You need to remove the permission faction.commands.fly
saschava: 
Ok
saschava: 
How do i dissable it
tobero: 
Remove the extension if installed
or
remove the permission faction.commands.fly from the default group

tobero: 
Hi, I'm back to developing improved factions once again. I've encountered challenges with multiple servers. Specifically, I'm facing difficulties with faction messages, as I need to emit and receive events across multiple applications. I believe using a message broker would be the best solution, but because I don't really know what's best for minecraft servers, I wanted to ask if someone has experience with setting up a server network (Bungeecord like or Multipaper) what broker I should use (If any). 
Currently, I've looked into two options. They're are Apache Kafka and RabbitMQ. They're both message brokers and I don't know which one to use.

I would appreciate your input on which message broker to use, or if there's another one that might be better suited for Minecraft plugins. Thank you!

sparrowvalentine: 
Hi, is there dynmap support for your plugin? @[Dev] Tobero
tobero: 
Yeah, it supports dynmap. But I've heard that people have issues getting it to display the chunks correctly
sparrowvalentine: 
Do I need to get a separate plugin for it to work?
tobero: 
Just improved factions and dynmap. When both things are installed, type `/f extension install` (Maybe extension**s**, not sure right now). This will open a menu and you can click a extension you want. Once downloaded, restart / reload your server and the extension should get loaded.

But please be warned: This plugin is a big pile of garbage right now. I'm working on a fix right now, but it might take me 1 - 2 week until it's ready for release

tobero: 
https://github.com/ToberoCat/GuiEngine/wiki/User-Beginner-Guide
Here's a whole guide on how to create your own gui.
If you need a example, here's the one from the guide:
```xml
<gui width="9" height="4" title="¬ßbMy first gui">
    <component type="item" x="5" y="2" material="REDSTONE_BLOCK" name="¬ßcSuspicious red button">
        <lore>¬ß7A button</lore>
        <lore>¬ß7You shouldn't click me</lore>
        <on-click type="action">[message] ¬ßcYou shouldn't have clicked me...</on-click>
        <on-click type="action">[player] summon zombie</on-click>
        <on-click type="action">[close]</on-click>
    </component>
    <component type="item" id="green-button" x="3" y="2" material="GREEN_TERRACOTTA" name="¬ßaGreen button">
        <lore>¬ß7Click me</lore>
        <lore>¬ß7I promise ¬ßait's worth¬ß7 it</lore>
        <on-click type="edit" target="green-button" attribute="name" set-value="¬ßeYou clicked me :)"/>
        <on-click type="edit" target="green-button" attribute="material" set-value="YELLOW_TERRACOTTA"/>
    </component>
</gui>
```
jokbon:

tobero: 
Yeah, you can create items, which will open a gui. This is a feature I've added so you are less dependent on external plugins.

Btw, the guide assumes you have zero knowledge about anything, so I think you're safe to skip some of the sections

tobero: 
The paged GUI is a container that allows you to just tell it which slots you want filled. Then you give it the components and it will page them.

If you want to make implement different files, you'll have to set the pattern to "0" (Meaning a single slot per page).

Then you add compontens type of embedded, which will link to the GUI files

(ok i understand more what i did wrong)

Embedded takes a target GUI, which is basically the name you use when calling /guiengine open
tobero: 
Then it will show the whole GUI in the gui

tobero: 
Yep. There are already two things that are redundant in this example. The paged component doesn't need a name attribute. As the paged component is a type of container managing the layout, values like x and y will be ignored and get managed by the paged component's slots.


So a version that fixes the pattern typo, as well as removes the redundand properties would look like this:
```xml
    <component type="paged" pattern="0,1,2,3,4,5" id="container" y="4" width="9" height="1">
        <component type="item" material="IRON_SWORD" name="¬ßcSuspicious red button">
            <on-click type="action">[message] ¬ß2Atempting to go to world </on-click>
            <on-click type="action">[close]</on-click>
        </component>
    </component>
```

tobero: 
Speed is pretty shitty to be true when the code you write is shit.
There's probably a reason why he's so fast, cause he doesn't think about the general structure all to much.
To get my code cleaner, I tried to follow a few principal (I made them up for myself):
- Low nesting => Everything needs to be a separate function
- Interfaces, just throw them at it and everything will be cleaner (For me at least)
- Try to "vectorize" stuff (eg, just use map, filter, etc)
- Best pretty nullsafity comes from optionals (Java) or just short hand null checks (Kotlin)
-Make a separate class for everything.

At least that's the stuff I follow when writing code (where I know how the structure)

tobero: 
No. You must create the next / previous buttons on your own. Once you create a paged component, you get two new actions.
[<componentId>:next] this will switch to the next page
[<componentId>:previous] this will switch to the previous page

jokbon:

tobero: 
To understand it, you need to understand what the paged component actually does.
At the base level, you can think of it as a component creating a in-memory gui for each page. The, calling next / previous, will update a embedded component's target to point at the paged gui.

Originally, I used it to allow developers to display lists of elements in a gui. To know where they have to be placed, I introduced the pattern. The pattern defines the position of a component on a page.
This mechanic itself would **not** allow you to do that, as you place them like this, the x / y will be ignored.

Because the paged component is when it comes down just a fancy embedded component, I added a shorthand property to create in-memory guis that will replace the target. They're called: `<page></page>`. They're just wrappers for your `<gui></gui>` inheriting the properties of the paged component. To define pages directly, bypassing the pattern, you can do something like this:

```xml
<gui title="¬ßeName" width="9" height="3">
    <component type="paged" pattern="5, 7">
        <page>
            <component type="item" x="4" y="1"
                       material="EMERALD_BLOCK"
                       name="¬ßaClick me!">
                <on-click type="action">[message] You clicked me!</on-click>
            </component>
        </page>
        <page>
            <component type="item" x="5" y="2"
                       material="GOLD_BLOCK"
                       name="¬ßaClick me!">
                <on-click type="action">[message] You clicked me!</on-click>
            </component>
        </page>
        <component type="item"
                   material="DIRT"
                   name="¬ßaClick me!">
            <on-click type="action">[message] You clicked me!</on-click>
        </component>
    </component>
</gui>
```

You can see, I create two pages and while defining some component positions explicitly, I can also use the pattern to create them automatically

tobero: 
It's just when you stack stuff in it's body. Like this:

```xml
<component>
  <component>
    <component>
      <!-- 3 Level Nesting -->
    </componet>
  </component>
<component>
```

Usually the more nested stuff gets, the more complex it's branching / data flow is

Attachments:
[image.png]
https://cdn.discordapp.com/attachments/819947051059118111/1148688967802298398/image.png?ex=66484d37&is=6646fbb7&hm=2ef2162c5a4cf45f775a3002164e59f4e25bc7fc3814ab334a0f62e30f22aa81&

tobero: 
Oh, yeah, you mean that. This is something special I've implemented for performance.

```SPOILER: A bunch of technical stuff about the inner workings of GuiEngine no body has to worry about as long as it works```
GuiEngine has three steps when processing a gui:
- Parsing Stage. This is where the interpreter converts the file into a in-memory representation of it, taking care of the syntatic sugar, etc. This is where you get the parsing issues, like missing >, or missing </, etc.
This step currently manages placeholders and is only done **a single time** per open call

- Context Interpretation. This is where the in-memory representation get parsed. Before it was just a bunch of strings. I will usually refer to it as the interpretation step. This is where the interpreter does all the heavy lifting. It will Chooses which type corresponds to which class, then uses this information to collect the properties and then converts these properties to the required data types, like a item.

- Render Stage. This step then takes the components and puts them into the a minecraft inventory. This is one by the GuiRenderEngine which gets provided by the interpreter.

The parse and interpret step run in a separate thread, as they don't interact with any minecraft logic.

This separation is needed, so I don't have to call all three steps when the page changes. When the page changes, the render engine gets called to update the inventories affected slots. 

As I've already mentioned, all steps have to be done when opening a gui - and this is a issue, because when having many players open guis, even when the gui doesn't change, it would in theory still go through all three steps, which wastes resources (You have probably already spotted the gui engine metrics about processing). On average it takes 15ms on my machine to load 10.000 guis. These 15ms aren't much, but when done many times, it will still create lags.
tobero: 
That's why guiengine actually checks when virtualizing guis to check if they're also runtime save (No endless loops, etc), the type. It will store the unviewed gui and compare it to the one after being viewed. When the content doesn't change, GuiEngine knows that this gui isn't being modified when running though the first two time steps, which makes them redundant. The gui is then being marked as static.
If the content changes (Because of placeholders or java logic doing things), guiengine marks it as dynamic.

This distinction helps reduce the gui opening time drastically.
When you turn on the debug info messages in the console, you'll see that guiengine logs the time it took for each gui indivually to render, as well as the time per step. This is usually 1 - 2ms for the first step, 10 - 12ms for the third and 2 - 3 ms for the  render step.
Therefore being able to skip the first two steps will make a huge difference in performance. To skip them, guiengine caches all static guis preprocessed, ready to render - And that's why /guiengine reload comes into play. When reloading, the cache get invalided, so you can view your guis after changes - But I personally found that annoying, so I've implemented a file watcher. It will see when changes have been made to a gui file and update their caches instantly uppon changes have been detected. This doesn't work for new files, so you still need the reload command when you add new files.

[config.yml]
update-checker: true
mysql:
  host: "localhost"
  port: 3306
  database: "improvedfactions"
  user: "root"
  password: "1234"
  verbose: false

rabbitmq:
  host: "localhost"
  port: 5672
  user: "guest"
  password: "guest"
  virtual-host: "/"

factions:
  max-rank-name-length: 50
  rank-name-regex: "[a-zA-Z ]*"
  max-spaces-in-name: 5
  # Unit is minutes
  invites-expire-in: 5
  name-regex: "[a-zA-Z ]*"

  # Default ranks every faction will receive once created. When modifying it,
  # note that the first rank will be set to be the default rank for members joining,
  # while the last one will be considered as the owner rank, the rank the owner will receive on faction creation
  default-faction-ranks:
    Member:
      priority: 1 # The priority this rank has
      # Defines the faction permissions this rank has by default. Can always be changed by factions
      default-permissions:
        - send-invites
    Elder:
      priority: 10
      default-permissions:
        - send-invites
        - manage-claims
    Admin:
      priority: 100
      default-permissions:
        - send-invites
        - manage-claims
        - manage-permissions
        - kick-player
        - manage-bans
    Owner:
      priority: 1000
      default-permissions:
        - send-invites
        - manage-claims
        - set-icon
        - rename-faction
        - manage-permissions
        - kick-player
        - manage-bans
        - transfer-ownership
  # Whenever you change values in this section, you'll have issues with your database
  # Choose values that go for you and never touch them again
  unsafe:
    guest-rank-name: "Guest"
    max-name-length: 36
    # Define how long the item in base64 format can get. Bigger numbers allow more complex items, while costing more space
    max-icon-length: 5000

# Changing these settings requires a server restart / reload to take effect,
# Please note: Once a zone has been added and got used on the server, it might be difficult to remove all references
# to it again, so only add zones you know you want to keep in the long run
zones:
  # Don't remove this zone ever. If you do, this will cause extremely weird
  # behavior of the plugin, which is almost impossible to trace back
  default:
    announce-title: true # True will allow this zone to send titles to the player - Faction claims and no faction claims
    allow-claiming: true # Set to true will allow factions to claim their chunks in these regions
    # This is the language key of the title getting displayed when a claimed chunk is being left into an unclaimed one
    no-faction-title: base.zone.wilderness
    always-protect: false # If set to true, all chunks, even unclaimed ones, will be affected from the protection rules defined below

    # Protection rules - Define how chunks should get protected. They only apply for people not owning the chunk (Except always-protect) has been set to true
    protection:
      animal-damage: true # Prevent animals from being damaged in a claim
      villager-damage: true # Prevent villagers from being damaged in a claim
      golem-damage: false # Prevent damage to Iron Golems in a claim
      monster-damage: false # Prevent damage caused by monsters in a claim
      boss-damage: false # Prevent damage caused by bosses in a claim
      general-pvp: false # Prevent general PvP in a claims. This means any sort of pvp
      in-faction-pvp: true # Prevent PvP between faction members in a claim
      minecart-damage: true # Prevent minecarts being destroyed in a claim
      block-place: true # Prevent placing blocks in a claim
      entity-spawned-by-egg: true # Prevent spawning entities using spawn eggs in a claim
      explosions: false # Prevent explosions to occur in a claim
      block-break: true # Prevent breaking blocks in a claim
      block-interaction: true # Prevent interacting with blocks in a claim
      entity-interaction: true # Prevent interacting with entities in a claim
      entity-break-hanging: true # Prevent breaking hanging entities (like paintings or itemframes) in a claim
  safezone:
    announce-title: true # True will allow this zone to send titles to the player - Faction claims and no faction claims
    allow-claiming: false # Set to true will allow factions to claim their chunks in these regions
    # This is the language key of the title getting displayed when a claimed chunk is being left into an unclaimed one
    no-faction-title: base.zone.safezone
    always-protect: true # If set to true, all chunks, even unclaimed ones, will be affected from the protection rules defined below

    # Protection rules - Define how chunks should get protected. They only apply for people not owning the chunk (Except always-protect) has been set to true
    protection:
      animal-damage: true # Prevent animals from being damaged in a claim
      villager-damage: true # Prevent villagers from being damaged in a claim
      golem-damage: true # Prevent damage to Iron Golems in a claim
      monster-damage: false # Prevent damage caused by monsters in a claim
      boss-damage: false # Prevent damage caused by bosses in a claim
      general-pvp: true # Prevent general PvP in a claims. This means any sort of pvp
      in-faction-pvp: true # Prevent PvP between faction members in a claim
      minecart-damage: true # Prevent minecarts being destroyed in a claim
      block-place: true # Prevent placing blocks in a claim
      entity-spawned-by-egg: true # Prevent spawning entities using spawn eggs in a claim
      explosions: true # Prevent explosions to occur in a claim
      block-break: true # Prevent breaking blocks in a claim
      block-interaction: true # Prevent interacting with blocks in a claim
      entity-interaction: true # Prevent interacting with entities in a claim
      entity-break-hanging: true # Prevent breaking hanging entities (like paintings or itemframes) in a claim
  warzone:
    announce-title: true # True will allow this zone to send titles to the player - Faction claims and no faction claims
    allow-claiming: false # Set to true will allow factions to claim their chunks in these regions
    # This is the language key of the title getting displayed when a claimed chunk is being left into an unclaimed one
    no-faction-title: base.zone.warzone
    always-protect: true # If set to true, all chunks, even unclaimed ones, will be affected from the protection rules defined below

    # Protection rules - Define how chunks should get protected. They only apply for people not owning the chunk (Except always-protect) has been set to true
    protection:
      animal-damage: false # Prevent animals from being damaged in a claim
      villager-damage: false # Prevent villagers from being damaged in a claim
      golem-damage: false # Prevent damage to Iron Golems in a claim
      monster-damage: false # Prevent damage caused by monsters in a claim
      boss-damage: false # Prevent damage caused by bosses in a claim
      general-pvp: false # Prevent general PvP in a claims. This means any sort of pvp
      in-faction-pvp: true # Prevent PvP between faction members in a claim
      minecart-damage: true # Prevent minecarts being destroyed in a claim
      block-place: true # Prevent placing blocks in a claim
      entity-spawned-by-egg: false # Prevent spawning entities using spawn eggs in a claim
      explosions: false # Prevent explosions to occur in a claim
      block-break: true # Prevent breaking blocks in a claim
      block-interaction: true # Prevent interacting with blocks in a claim
      entity-interaction: true # Prevent interacting with entities in a claim
      entity-break-hanging: true # Prevent breaking hanging entities (like paintings or itemframes) in a claim
  unmanaged:
    announce-title: false # True will allow this zone to send titles to the player - Faction claims and no faction claims

```[10:12:05] [Server thread/INFO]: [ImprovedFactions] [STDOUT] SQL: SELECT
                  rc.CONSTRAINT_NAME,
                  ku.TABLE_NAME,
                  ku.COLUMN_NAME,
                  ku.REFERENCED_TABLE_NAME,
                  ku.REFERENCED_COLUMN_NAME,
                  rc.UPDATE_RULE,
                  rc.DELETE_RULE
                FROM INFORMATION_SCHEMA.REFERENTIAL_CONSTRAINTS rc
                  INNER JOIN INFORMATION_SCHEMA.KEY_COLUMN_USAGE ku
                    ON ku.TABLE_SCHEMA = rc.CONSTRAINT_SCHEMA AND rc.CONSTRAINT_NAME = ku.CONSTRAINT_NAME
                WHERE ku.TABLE_SCHEMA = 's339_factions'
                  AND ku.CONSTRAINT_SCHEMA = 's339_factions'
                  AND rc.CONSTRAINT_SCHEMA = 's339_factions'
                  AND  ku.TABLE_NAME IN ('faction_users')
                ORDER BY ku.ORDINAL_POSITION

tobero: 
These errors are just warnings, the first one just tells you no message broker is setup, which isn't needed.
The second one tells oyu that the configured mysql server hasn't been found and it's using sqlite instead - Basically, just things to inform you that it's not using any external tools, nothing serious in your case.

So the error must be somewhere else.

Would you be able to send the latest.txt?

jokbon: 
not modules but more commands to manage factions
dynamic taxation (run command to set factions tax bonus/penality run command to remove)
dynamic power (run command to set factions power bonus run command to remove)
dynamic max power (run command to set factions power bonus run command to remove)
power bonuses (run command to set factions power bonus run command to remove)
tobero: 
What are bonuses exactly?
jokbon: 
commands that add power to faction
jokbon: 
or retract
jokbon: 
for example: faction needs to achieve something to get +2 max power per member
tobero: 
You mean the admin commands? There's already /f power <add|set> <maxpower|accumulated> <amount> <faction>
tobero: 
Oh, you mean like a per member bonus
jokbon: 
faction raided someone, penality -2 power per member
tobero: 
Okay, like event based power bonuses / penalities. I think I should be able to at least provide the base commands
jokbon: 
run command when someone raids a chunk
jokbon: 
yep like event based
jokbon: 
but integrated with other plugins like conditional events
jokbon: 
so in general its just a command
jokbon: 
```dynamic taxation (run command to set factions tax bonus/penality; run command to remove)
dynamic power (run command to set factions power bonus/penality; run command to remove)
dynamic max power (run command to set factions power bonus/penality; run command to remove)
power bonuses (run command to set factions power bonus/penality; run command to remove)```

tobero: 
As I don't have the time to reproduce the error locally, I've built this file. It contains a potential fix for it, as this error looks like it's caused by the plugin trying to access data from the database while the database is still being created. This file should now fix this issue.

If it still doesn't work, try removing the database.sqlite file in the plugin's directory located at plugins/ImprovedFactions/database.sqlite. This will force the plugin to regenerate the database.

If the generated database still gives errors, I've attached the database.sqlite file that starts on my local instance
